          "title": "Praise as the weapon of faith",
          "body": "The chapter's most theologically provocative moment is the appointment of singers to march before the army singing 'Give thanks to the LORD, for His lovingkindness is everlasting' (20:21). The anthem is drawn from Psalm 136, whose refrain repeats the phrase about chesed twenty-six times — the very psalm that rehearses the Exodus and wilderness miracles. The singers are not singing about the battle ahead; they are singing about who God has always been. And the Chronicler's timing is precise: 'when they began singing and praising, the LORD set ambushes' (20:22). Praise is the trigger of divine military action, not its celebration after the fact. This is not magical thinking; it is covenant theology made kinetic. The singers are proclaiming God's chesed in advance of its visible demonstration, which is the very definition of faith (cf. Hebrews 11:1). Keller observes that praise is the act of making God's character more real to the soul than the circumstances — Jehoshaphat's choir is doing exactly that."
